        updatedBy: '532',
        label: 'Clericus Phase II',
        content:
          "<p>September 2020 marks the beginning of Phase II of the Clericus Project, a digital humanities initiative based in the Arts and Humanities Institute, Maynooth University. Following a successful partnership with St. Patrick’s College Maynooth in Phase I, the project aims to expand its database on the Irish clerical population and digital preservation initiative through collaboration with several new institutions. This will include working closely with a number of diocesan seminaries to identify and ingest several thousand additional biographical records for clerical students covering the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. Where available, it is also planned to digitally capture and preserve student class pieces and other artefacts of historical significance.</p>\n<p>The project further aims to expand the database’s existing information on clerical students through the addition of biographical data relating to the ministry of a subset of the clerical population. This will involve extracting relevant data from one of Ireland’s diocesan histories. Apart from deepening our understanding of individual career paths and networks, this will permit the project to further test, develop and showcase the database’s dynamic qualities through the integration and synergy of data from several heterogeneous sources. This, in turn, will offer the practical experience and customised system necessary to handle a range of new sources and data during future phases of the project.</p>\n<p>The second phase will also see the project expand its temporal range to include data from the early modern period. Several of the most comprehensive records for Ireland’s seventeenth- and eighteenth-century Catholic clergy have been identified, and their inclusion will once again help to expand the database’s value to researchers from different disciplines. In particular, the mapping of this data will add a new dimension to the study and understanding of the clerical population during what was both a turbulent and formative period in their history.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>The second phase project team are:</p>\n<p>Prof Thomas O'Connor, Principal Investigator</p>\n<p>Stavros Angelis, Chief Technical Officer</p>\n<p>Dr Richard Fitzpatrick, Research Assistant &amp; Content Manager</p>\n<p>September 2020</p>",
