        updatedBy: '53930',
        label: 'Content Delivery Public Interface',
        content:
          '<p>The Content Delivery Public Interface is a user interface build with <a href="https://reactjs.org/" target="_blank">React</a>, a Javascript framework. <a href="https://getbootstrap.com/" target="_blank">Bootstrap</a> is used as the main templating toolkit to ensure a modern, responsive layout. The <a href="https://d3js.org/" target="_blank">D3</a> library is being employed for the graph data visualisations, expanded with <a href="https://www.pixijs.com/" target="_blank">PixiJS</a> for better performance and more efficient rendering. <a href="https://leafletjs.com/" target="_blank">Leaflet</a> is the javascript library employed for making the responsive map visualisations. Finally <a href="https://sass-lang.com/" target="_blank">Sass</a>, an extension to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSS" target="_blank">CSS</a> stylesheet language, is being employed to add modern and efficient styling to the application.</p>\n<p>The CDPI offers access to the data and content of the project. The user experience adn navigation has been developed through many circles of software requirements specification with the content team of the project and a user experience exercise with domain experts of different backgrounds where, among others, the Usability, Utility and Desirability of the application were measured.</p>\n<h4>Main Features</h4>\n<p>The CDPI is organised in views and components. The Home screen is the main entry view where users are presented with a custom carousel that showcases interesting aspects of the collection, some interesting statistics about the contents of the collection, general information about the project, article highlights about important figures in the Clericus project population, the project news, a welcome text and direct access to the available visualisations.</p>\n<p>An articles\' list and an article view are available. For all article categories and articles, search engine optimised permalinks are automatically created by the system. Each article contains rich content and details about the creator of the article and the date of the last update.</p>\n<p>A classpieces grid view is available. Through this view visitors may search and browse through classpieces and filter them by related event types and dates.</p>\n<p>An individual classpiece view is also available. This view contains all details related to a classpiece (e.g. when the classpiece was compiled, which people are depicted on the classpiece etc) as well as a custom classpiece viewer. Through the classpiece viewer visitors can see details about people depicted on the classpiece by hovering the mouse cursor over them and view the individual person\'s page by clicking into the marked area on the screen. A search functionality is also available that will highlight a selected person on the classpiece.</p>\n<p>A people list view is available. This view allows visitors to search for people and an advanced search feature is also available. Visitors may also filter results by related event types, related sources and dates.</p>\n<p>Similar list views and individual record views have been developed for the main entities of the data model, i) events, ii) organisations, iii) resources, iv) temporal and v) spatial. These views are not part of the main navigation but can still be accessed through links to individual related items and the navigation breadcrumbs.</p>\n<p>Three main visualisation components have been developed to provide visitors with more intuitive ways to view, understand and interact with the data. These are i) the heatmap, ii) the events timeline and iii) the network graph.</p>\n<p>The Heatmap visualisation is a graphical representation of the distribution of people contained within the Clericus database, that are associated with a diocese. The heatmap shows hotspots depending on the number of people associated with a location. The color of each hotspot on the map indicates the population density for that location as shown in more detail in the legend at the bottom right corner of the heatmap. Depending on the zoom level the locations form clusters. When visitors put their mouse over a cluster a polygon appears with each location being represented by the appropriate polygon corner. Individual locations are represented by a marker pin. Clicking on a marker pin will open a small popup with the locations details, i.e. the name of the associated diocese and it\'s associated people. The heatmap component is a custom component based on <a href="https://leafletjs.com/" target="_blank">Leaflet</a>.</p>\n<p>The Events timeline is a graphical representation of the events list ordered in chronological order. Each item of this list shows a date and the number of associated events with that date. The items are color coded to make it easier for the visitors to distinguish between them. Clicking on an item will open up a small popup window with the list of all associated events with that date. Clicking on the event will show all associated entities with that event. The Events timeline is a custom component built specifically for the project\'s needs.</p>\n<p>The Network graph visualisation represents the list of relationships between the various entities held in the Clericus database. Each node has a different color according to it\'s type, as explained in the legend at the bottom right corner. Clicking on a node will open up a popup window showing the node details. All related nodes and links between the selected node and the related nodes will be highlighted as well. This node details window contains the label and type of the node and it\'s related nodes. The visitor can extend that selection by updating the steps between the selected node and the related nodes. This means that when steps is set to 1 only nodes that are directly related with the selected node will be shown. If the steps are set to 2 all nodes that are directly related with the selected node will be shown as well as all the nodes that are related with them, thus extending the associated network by one step. Upon updating the steps all related nodes and links will be highlighted. The Network graph visualisation is a process that heavily affects the performance of the system. Many optimisation and caching techniques were used to minimise any possible performance drop for the visitors, however the number of entities and relationships represented on this visualisation can be too much for the visitor\'s browser. The Network graph component has been built on <a href="https://d3js.org/" target="_blank">D3</a> and <a href="https://www.pixijs.com/" target="_blank">PixiJS</a> has been employed to achieve better performance.</p>\n<p>The visualisations components are always under development. As the database grows and expands we try to find better ways to represent the data and optimise the performance of the visualisations.</p>',
