        updatedBy: '53930',
        label: 'Events help',
        content:
          "<p>The Events page is made by two columns, the <strong>Filters</strong> column on the left and the Events column on the right.</p>\n<h4>Filters</h4>\n<p>The <strong>Filters</strong> column allows the visitor to filter the list of items shown in the Events column. The available filter are: </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Event type</li>\n<li>Dates</li>\n</ol>\n<h5>Event type</h5>\n<p>The <strong>Event type</strong> filter allows the visitor to filter the events' list according to the available events types.</p>\n<h5>Dates</h5>\n<p>The <strong>Dates</strong> filter allows the visitor to filter by dates. First the visitor must select the type of the date match from a drop down list. The date match type may be one of the following: </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Exact</li>\n<li>Before</li>\n<li>After</li>\n<li>In Range</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If the visitor selects one of the three first types she/he then must set the date. A datepicker is available to help select the proper date easier and ensure that the date is supplied in the correct format (dd/mm/yyyy). If the visitor selects the last option, In Range one input appears to allow the visitor to input the appropriate end date.<br />The visitor must trigger the filter by clicking on the submit button.</p>\n<h5>General remarks</h5>\n<p>The filters work in combination. Each time a visitor selects a filter the filters themselves are also filtered and only the values that may be applied to the available subset of classpieces remain visible, thus enabling further filtering the results.</p>\n<p>Every search filter has a small <em><strong>clear </strong></em>button. This button clears only the selected values of that specific filter. There is also a generic <em><strong>clear all </strong></em>button next to the <strong>Filters</strong> heading that clears all the selected filters. </p>\n<p>When a visitor sets filters the filter values are stored in the memory. When the visitor navigates back to the classpieces webpage the filters are still active. This memory is reset when the visitor refreshes the webpage or opens it in a new window/tab.</p>\n<h4>Events</h4>\n<p>The events column contains the following:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>the number of total items</li>\n<li>the search bar</li>\n<li>the limit dropdown list</li>\n<li>the pagination</li>\n<li>the list of events</li>\n</ol>\n<h5>Number of total items</h5>\n<p>This number is updated when the visitor sets filters and/or performs a search to reflect the total number of matches.</p>\n<h5>Search bar</h5>\n<p>The search bar visibility may be toggled by clicking the lens icon next to the number of total items. The search bar has a generic search input where the visitor may enter a search term. This term is matched against the labels of the events and the results are returned. To submit the search the visitor may either press the enter key or click on the search button next to the search input. The search input contains a round x button that works as a clear search button, when a visitor clicks this button the search term is removed and the system returns all the events.</p>\n<h5>Limit</h5>\n<p>The Limit dropdown is where the visitor sets the number of items she/he wishes to view per page.</p>\n<h5>Pagination</h5>\n<p>The pagination allows the visitor to navigate through the available pages of events. The visitor may navigate to the first/last page, next/previous page or to a page number. The user may also input a page number directly, a feature that may prove useful when there is a very big number of pages.</p>\n<h5>List of events</h5>\n<p>The list of events contains a list of the available events per page. This list changes according to the filters set by the visitor and the search term. Each item in the list contains the thumbnail of a event and the label of the event.</p>",
