        label:
          'Irish College Paris (ICP) entries added to the Clericus database',
        content:
          "<p>The Clericus database now includes over 2,000 new biographical entries relating to Irish clerical students educated in the Irish College Paris (ICP). Similar to other Irish colleges on the continent, the foundation of the ICP during the late sixteenth century stemmed from the attempted suppression of the Catholic Church in Ireland by successive English monarchs and their administrations. The Counter-Reformation requirement to set up Catholic seminaries and later, the restrictions placed on education for Catholics in Ireland by the Penal Laws, would eventually see 30 Irish colleges established across Europe, with the largest and most important of these being the Irish College in Paris. The college's 300 years of history was complex and mutifacted, and the reader interested in learning more about the college's story is directed to the following article <a href=\"https://www.centreculturelirlandais.com/content/files/History-CCI-English.pdf\">'The Irish Colleges in Paris,1578 - 2002: History'</a>.</p>\n<p>and other, oftentimes humorous, scandalous or tragic observations regarding students and their behaviour. Thus, in 1872 <a href=\"../person/66520\">Michael McCormack</a> of Cashel and Emly diocese was 'expelled for introducing brandy into the college', while several years later, <a href=\"../person/68100\">John Murray</a> of Cloyne diocese was 'detected in a secret and suspicious correspondence with persons outside; required to leave'.</p>\n<p>The value of the data to members of the public researching their family history is increased due to the inclusion of parents' names (including maiden names) for over half of the students. Almost 200 ICP students would also spend time studying at St Patrick's College Maynooth (SPCM), which in turn deepens our understanding of individual career paths. One excellent example to highlight this enrichment process is seen in <a href=\"../person/9027\">Kevin Clark</a> of Meath diocese, whose database entry draws on information from every resource utilised within the Clericus system thus far. </p>",
