        label: 'Irish College grave at Arcueil',
        content:
          '<p>The accompanying image is of the grave plot and memorial belonging to eleven deceased members of the Irish College Paris interred at <a href="../spatial/71907">Arcueil</a> (Cachan) cemetery between 1859 and 1891.</p>\n<p>In 1834, Dr. Patrick McSweeney, superior of the Irish College, \'purchased a country house of the college at Arcuil (sic.), one hour’s walk from Paris. It consists of a large building with six acres of land beautifully planted.\' For over one hundred years this house and its accompanying grounds, including a much used GAA pitch, played host to hundreds of young Irishmen being educated for the priesthood (see 19th century maps and plans of Arcueil <a href="https://archives-en.centreculturelirlandais.com/ark:74216/1eab6ba102876450a5490050569c4128.fiche=arko_fiche_5e7db3e80f034.moteur=arko_default_5f10436c8cf5a">here</a>). Canon <a href="../person/61318">Séamus Corkery</a>, who studied at the Irish College in the 1930s, writes that he and his fellow seminarians went to Arcueil twice a week, often on foot from rue des Irlandais in Paris (the Irish College), to play gaelic football and hurling matches in the grounds of the country house. \'We used to have mini All-Ireland’s…Competition was always keen,\' he writes, and at Christmas \'some enterprising student might get a goose from home and we would have a party.\'</p>\n<p>By the time Corkery revisited Paris (possibly during the early 1990s), the house at Arcueil and its playing fields had long been demolished and replaced by council flats. Upon visiting the college graves at Cachan cemetery, he was dismayed to find the plots neglected as \'no one ever contributed to their upkeep\'. Following his return to Ireland, Corkery set about raising awareness of the abandoned graves and funds were made available for their upkeep. This included the grave pictured above. However, two adjacent plots belonging to the college have yet to be restored.</p>\n<p>All the individuals recorded on the grave memorial pictured above were either current seminarians and/or members of the college\'s teaching faculty (<a href="../person/60930">William Cleary</a>) at the time of their passing. The college\'s records provide the causes of death in several instances, such as consumption (<a href="../person/62920">John Fitzgerald</a>), small pox (<a href="../person/64875">Edward Kelly)</a>, typhoid fever (<a href="../person/71572">Michael Walsh</a>) and inflammation of the lungs (<a href="../person/69169">Andrew O\'Hanlon</a>). These sudden losses amongst such a young and closeknit community were often keenly felt by the students and faculty alike, as evident in the record of Andrew O\'Hanlon\'s passing, being described as \'a most edifying young man\'.</p>\n<p>Unfortunately, two of the eleven deceased do not appear in the surviving college records (John McCann and Patrick Campbell). Many more students died in Ireland having returned home due to illness or while on vacation - consumption, pneumonia and meningitis appear to have been the main causes of death, while alcohol abuse and a gun accident are also noted. The college archive further records the loss of nearly a dozen other students in France during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, and it is to be assumed that several are interred in the two Arcueil plots in need of restoration. Some of the individuals who were possibly laid to rest in these plots are:</p>\n<p><a href="../person/67493">Anthony Meehan</a> (d. 6-02-1921)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/62082">Hugh Dever</a> (d. 30-06-1856)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/62842">James Finegan</a> (d. c.1913)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/65698">Michael Mackey</a> (d. 5-12-1852)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/66188">Bernard McCabe</a> (d. c.1903)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/66595">James McDavin</a>/McDavitt/McDevitt (d. 3-10-1853)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/66663">James McDonnell</a> (d. c.1896)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/67141">Peter McKeone</a> (d. c.1898)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/62908">James Fitzgerald</a> (d. 14-09-1853)</p>\n<p><a href="../person/67123">William McKenna</a> (d. July 1936)</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>Sources:</p>\n<p>\'Faint traces in Arcueil\', available <a href="http://www.irish-paris.net/saints-and-churchmen/faint-traces-in-arcueil">here</a></p>\n<p>Liam Chambers, \'The Irish College in Paris, 1578-2002\', available <a href="https://www.centreculturelirlandais.com/content/files/History-CCI-English.pdf">here</a></p>\n<p>\'The country house at Arcueil, with a manuscript estate survey, in ink and wash, of the buildings, courtyards, gardens and parklands that comprised the Collège des Irlandais at Arcueil\', available at: the Irish Cultural Centre Maps and <a href="https://archives-en.centreculturelirlandais.com/archives-en/maps-and-plans">Plans</a></p>\n<p>\'November: remembering our dead - the Irish College grave at Arcueil Cachan\', available at: Irish Chaplaincy, <a href="http://www.irishchaplaincyparis.fr/2017/11/november-remembering-our-dead-the-irish-college-grave-at-arcueil-cachan-the-irish-college/">Paris</a> </p>\n<p>Our sincere thanks to Mgr. Hugh Connolly and the Irish Chaplaincy Paris for providing permission to repost the image of the ICP grave from their website.</p>\n<p>May 2021</p>',
